    "name": "COU1: Non-cannulated construct compression-bending prediction",
    "description": "FEA predicts construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw design under ASTM F1717 static compression-bending. Validated by direct comparison to bench testing (N=11 constructs across two laboratories). Model influence MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence MEDIUM (pedicle screw fracture leads to revision surgery, not death).",
    "intendedUse": "Demonstrate that the FEA modeling framework reproduces experimental compression-bending behavior of a non-cannulated pedicle screw construct within pre-established acceptance bounds (<10% QoI difference, E/uval < 1.96).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "decisionConsequence": "Medium",
    "deviceClass": "Class II"
  },
  "nodes": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/claim/fea-validates-noncannulated-construct",
      "type": "Claim",
      "name": "FEA model adequately predicts compression-bending behavior of the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw construct",
      "description": "This claim asserts that the finite element analysis (FEA) modeling framework, as implemented by the tri-laboratory ensemble (FDA, Ansys, DePuy Synthes), produces predictions of construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement that are within the pre-established acceptance bounds of 10% relative difference and a normalized validation metric E/uval < 1.96 for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw under ASTM F1717 static compression-bending loading. The claim is grounded in a comprehensive body of work spanning mesh convergence studies, material property characterization from tensile coupon testing, contact parameter sensitivity analyses, and direct comparison of FEA outputs against N=11 physical constructs tested across two independent laboratories. Geometric fidelity was confirmed through micro-CT reconstruction of representative screws, and boundary condition equivalence was established via load-cell and displacement transducer calibration records. The totality of this evidence base, documented in the associated validation report (Nagaraja et al., 2023), supports the conclusion that the model is fit for its intended regulatory purpose.",
      "purpose": "Regulatory submission support — demonstrate FEA model fitness for ASTM F1717 compression-bending prediction of non-cannulated pedicle screw construct",
      "scope": "Non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw; ASTM F1717 static compression-bending; construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement; N=11 experimental replicates; two independent test laboratories"
    }
  ],
